04301nam a22006735i 9783110755404DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022930308  a97831107554047 a10.1515/97831107554042doi  a(DE-B1597)586042  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aPHI0160002bisacsh1 aNemeth, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRussian Neo-Kantianism :bEmergence, Dissemination, and Dissolution /cThomas Nemeth. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (IX, 345 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Studies in the History and Historiography of Philosophy ,x2364-3161 ;v1000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 A Neo-Kantianian Look on Physics: Aleksandr Vvedenskij -- tChapter 2 The Problem of Other Minds: Lapshin, Khvostov, Lappo-Danilevskij -- tChapter 3 The Psychologist as a Transcendental Realist -- tChapter 4 Neo-Kantian Marxism: A Curious and Unstable Blend -- tChapter 5 Baden versus Marburg on Russian Soil -- tChapter 6 Baden Makes Inroads -- tChapter 7 Baden School Philosophers Who Scattered -- tChapter 8 The Marburg School’s Influence in Imperial Russia -- tChapter 9 One-Time Neo-Kantians Who Stayed: Sakketti, Two Rubinshtejns, Kagan -- tChapter 10 One-Time Neo-Kantians Who Strayed: Vejdeman, Jakovenko, Sezeman -- tChapter 11 Concluding Remarks -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis, the first in-depth and comprehensive book-length study of the Russian neo-Kantian movement in English language, challenges the assumption of the isolation of neo-Kantianism to Germany. The present investigation demonstrates that neo-Kantianism had an international dimension by showing the emergence of a parallel movement in Imperial Russia spanning its emergence in the late 19th century to its gradual dissolution in the aftermath of the Bolshevik Revolution. The author presents a systematic portrait of the development of Russian neo-Kantianism starting with its rise as a philosophy of science. However, it was with the stream of young students returning to Imperial Russia after a period of study at German universities that the movement accelerated. More often than not, these enthusiastic, young philosophers returned home imbued with the neo-Kantianism of their respective but divergent host institutions. As a result, clashes were inevitable concerning the proper approach to philosophical issues as well as the very understanding of Kant's philosophy and his legacy for contemporary thought. In the end, the broad promise of a Western-oriented neo-Kantianism could not withstand the pressures it confronted on all sides.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 4aIdealismus. 4aKant, Immanuel. 4aRealismus ‹Philosophie›. 4aRezeption. 4aRussland / Neukantianismus. 4aRussland / Philosophie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh0 cEPUBz97831107555340 cprintz978311075535040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311075540440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110755404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110755404/original  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK